[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1882-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1882 throughout the world.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1883-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1883 throughout the world.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1884-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1884 throughout the world.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1884-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1884-in-baseball] Old Hoss Radbourn won a record 59 or 60 games (depending on the sources), a record that will almost certainly never be broken.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1884-in-baseball] In addition to wins, Radbourn led the National League in games (75), games started (73), complete games (73), ERA (1.38), saves (2), strikeouts (441), and innings pitched (678.2).
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1884-in-baseball] The season record for pitching strikeouts (369, by Tim Keefe 1883) is broken by seven players, with Hugh Daily beating Keefe's record by 114.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1884-in-baseball] To this day (as of 2020), six of the top ten strikeout seasons were accomplished in 1884 (including five of the top seven).
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1884-in-baseball] 1884 was the first season in which pitchers were allowed to throw overhand.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1885-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1885 throughout the world.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1885-in-baseball] Post-season playoff: the Chicago White Stockings played the St.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1885-in-baseball] Louis Browns, which ended with both teams going 3–3–1 in a best-of-seven series.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1885-in-baseball] Game 1 finished in a tie called after eight innings due to darkness; Game 2 was awarded to Chicago by forfeit after six innings because St.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1885-in-baseball] Louis refused to continue after disputing an umpiring decision.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1885-in-baseball] Both teams dispute the series and claim the championship.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1886-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1886 throughout the world.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1887-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1887 throughout the world.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/1890-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1890 throughout the world.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/jackie-hayes-catcher] From 1882 to 1887, Hayes he played for seven different teams getting most of his playing time in his first two seasons when playing for the Worcester Ruby Legs, and the Pittsburgh Alleghenys.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/jackie-hayes-catcher] In 1890, he returned to major league baseball when he played for the Brooklyn Ward's Wonders.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/jackie-hayes-catcher] Hayes is known for one infamous game on June 17, 1885 when playing for the Brooklyn Grays, he and his teammates resented the arrival of Phenomenal Smith, whose brash demeanor didn't sit well with the veterans on the team, and committed 28 errors en route to an 18–5 loss to the St.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/jackie-hayes-catcher] Louis Browns, with Hayes committing seven of them.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/jackie-hayes-catcher] After the game, Charlie Byrne fired manager Charlie Hackett, and handed out heavy fines to the guilty players.
[src:jackie-hayes-catcher/jackie-hayes-catcher] Jackie Hayes died at the age of 43 in his hometown of Brooklyn, and is interred at Calvary Cemetery, Woodside, New York.
